<div class="mb-8 mt-8 rounded-lg p-2 border border-rose-200 dark:border-rose-800 bg-rose-100 dark:bg-rose-900/20 rounded-lg">
  <h3 id="learned1" class="font-semibold">Lesson 1: Style Guide</h3>
    <p class="ml-8">We understood this because, even though we had references for inspirations, without a concrete style guide, artists filled in gaps with their own styles, which caused noticiable differences in their work.</p>
</div>

<p class="mt-4">Our team had a big problem though in that we actually had no artists on the core team and so relied heavily on contract work from outside sources. We reached out to artists we knew and offered either paid contract work or school credit.</p>

<h2 id="production" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Art During Production</h2>
<p>During production the fact that we did not have a core artist started to show as not having a very solid style caused dissonance between artists' work. Luckily one of our tech art contractors implemented shaders for lighting and reflections which brought new layers of depth for the games art and helped bridge things like lineweight differences. Additionally, setting up a pipeline to have artists get their art into the engine directly while easy for some artists proved difficult for less technically savvy artists who felt much more comfortable placing things in a google drive. Our process of designing rooms with art was to emphasize the arches and pillars with a mix of decorative items such as plants, books, and more.</p>

<div class="mb-8 mt-8 rounded-lg p-2 border border-rose-200 dark:border-rose-800 bg-rose-100 dark:bg-rose-900/20 rounded-lg">
  <h3 id="learned2" class="font-semibold">Lesson 2: Asset Resolution<h3>
    <p class="ml-8">You need to have specific rules regarding resolution and you need to understand how your engine processes art before creating too many assets. We discovered this when utilizing Godot’s tilemap layer system where scaling tiles was much more static and different resolutions caused inconsistencies in the tile sets.</p>
</div>

<div class="mb-8 mt-8 rounded-lg p-2 border border-rose-200 dark:border-rose-800 bg-rose-100 dark:bg-rose-900/20 rounded-lg">
  <h3 id="learned3" class="font-semibold">Lesson 3: Managing External Artists</h3>
    <p class="ml-8">We assigned one core team member to manage all the art contractors that worked on our project. This was crucial in having consistent communication with the artists. </p>
</div>

<div class="mb-8 mt-8 rounded-lg p-2 border border-rose-200 dark:border-rose-800 bg-rose-100 dark:bg-rose-900/20 rounded-lg">
  <h3 id="learned4" class="font-semibold">Lesson 4: In-Engine Effects</h3>
    <p class="ml-8">While we got enough art to create a coherent game, without a core artist to consistently make assets it will always put a strain on the project.</p>
    <p class="ml-8">Instead, we should've focused on what we COULD do: in-engine effects (i.e. particles and shaders).</p>
</div>

